      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nCurrently, with the development of technologies such as GPS, GLONASS, Galileo, and BeiDou (<htcite0>), locating ourselves on Earth has become much simpler. However, we often use these technologies through applications without understanding the processes that occur behind them.\n\nIn the previous text, we were introduced to the concept of the Pythagorean Theorem (<htcite1>), fundamental to spatial location. In this text, we will delve a little deeper into the knowledge associated with it.\n\nBefore taking the first steps, reflect:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "f61cdce0-7753-4326-9d6d-1e7d431fda9c",
                     "text": "Logsdon, T.S.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "4",
                        "day": "20"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "50e702c5-bc41-1a5f-8d90-4585e04394ba",
                     "text": "History Tracers Atlas",
                     "page": "History of a Theorem",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Back and forth</b><br /><br />The Pythagorean Theorem is given by:<br /><br /> <math display=\"block\"><mrow> <mrow><msup><mi>a</mi><mn>2</mn></msup> <mo>+</mo> <msup><mi>b</mi><mn>2</mn></msup> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <msup><mi>c</mi> <mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></math><br /><br />When drawing it in a triangle, we can observe that it has three magnitudes: two legs (<b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and a hypotenuse (<b>c</b>), shown in <b>Chart 1</b> (<htcite0>).<br /><br />How would you work with them?</div></div></center>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "50e702c5-bc41-1a5f-8d90-4585e04394ba",
                     "text": "History Tracers Atlas",
                     "page": "History of a Theorem",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"unitaryCircle\" id=\"circtri0\"><style>.circle-draw circle, .circle-draw line {stroke: #71a6d2; stroke-width: 4; stroke-linecap: round; fill: none;} .circle-draw circle { stroke-dasharray: 942; stroke-dashoffset: 942;} .radius-line { transform-origin: 300px 150px} .radius-45 { opacity: 1} .radius-30{ opacity: 1 } .vertical45 { opacity: 1 } .atlasTextRadius { opacity: 1 }</style><div class=\"atlasCircleContainer\"><svg viewBox=\"0 0 600 180\" class=\"circle-draw\" id=\"svgcirctri0\">  <path class=\"radius-30\" d=\"M 260 127 A 30 30 0 0 1 270.0 150.0\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#71a6d2\" stroke-width=\"3\"/> <line class=\"radius-line\" x1=\"230\" y1=\"148\" x2=\"376\" y2=\"148\"></line> <line class=\"radius-45\" x1=\"230\" y1=\"148\" x2=\"376\" y2=\"46\"></line>  <line class=\"vertical45\" x1=\"376\" y1=\"46\" x2=\"376\" y2=\"146\"></line> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"300\" y=\"88\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">c</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"300\" y=\"168\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">a</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"380\" y=\"108\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">b</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"255\" y=\"145\" font-size=\"1.0em\" font-weight=\"bold\">θ</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"202\" y=\"155\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">O</text> <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"377\" y=\"45\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">P</text>  <text class=\"atlasTextRadius\" x=\"375\" y=\"162\" font-size=\"1.3em\" font-weight=\"bold\">Q</text></svg></div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Right triangle with named components.</p>",
