      {
         "id": "SECTION_equality",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### What is equality?\n\nAs a first step to understanding what the theorem tells us, we will begin with the depth of the equal sign (=) that appears in it. So, answer the following reflection before proceeding:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Equal or different</b><br /><br />When you read the phrase: “the two objects are equal,” what conclusion do you initially reach?<br /><br />Now, imagine I change only one object, for example, by painting it. Do the two objects remain equal?<br /><br />And if, afterwards, I paint the other object the same color? Would you return to your initial conclusion or remain with the conclusion from when only the first had been painted?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Being equal is not being different\n\nWhen we initially addressed equality in History Tracers, we learned that the equal sign is not a simple mark. It indicates that, between the compared elements, there is no difference whatsoever. If there are two equal objects and a person closes their eyes while we swap their positions, when they open them again they will not notice any difference, as in **Graph 2**.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "bb226b7f-2358-437f-b6e1-668943c682d7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Atlas",
                     "page": "Exploring equality",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htTwoGeometricalRectangle\"> <div class=\"htFirstGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\" style=\"height: 12vh; width: 12vh;\"></div></div> <div class=\"htSecondGeometrical\"><div class=\"htCircle\" style=\"height: 12vh; width: 12vh;\"></div></div> </div></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Graph 2</b>: Two identical circles.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### More than a sign\n\nThe equal sign, in any mathematical formula, can also be interpreted as a law, which tells us that if any action is performed on one side, it must necessarily be repeated on the other.\n\nTo visualize this better, let's redo an exercise presented in another text (<htcite0>) using our hands.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "bb226b7f-2358-437f-b6e1-668943c682d7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Atlas",
                     "page": "Exploring equality",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Equal sides</b><br />We will use both of our hands in this practice.<br /><br />1. Close the fingers of both hands. With all fingers down, both represent zero.<br />2. Raise the index finger of each hand. By raising the same fingers, we still keep our hands showing the same quantities; now both show 1.<br />3. Repeat the previous step, raising one finger from each hand simultaneously.<br /><br />If you have any questions about how to perform the practice, you can use the arrows in Table 1, presented below, to visualize the activity in action. Then, do the exercise with your own fingers.<br /></div></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"yupana0\" class=\"tawapukllay\"><tr><th colspan=\"4\"><i>Equation</i></th><th>Left hand</th><th>Right hand</th><th>Arrows</th></tr> <tr id=\"tf1\"><td id=\"tc1f1\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"leftnum\">0</span></td></td> <td id=\"tc2f1\" colspan=\"2\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\">=</span></td> <td id=\"tc4f1\"><span class=\"text_to_paint\" id=\"rightnum\">0</span></td><td id=\"tc5f1\" style=\"background-color:white;\"><img id=\"leftHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('leftHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Left_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc6f1\"><img id=\"rightHandImg\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('rightHandImg', '0%')\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/0Right_Hand_Small.png\" /></td><td id=\"tc7f1\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-up upArrowWithFA\" id=\"traineeUp0\"></i>  <i class=\"fa-solid fa-caret-down downArrowWithFA\"style=\"font-size:4em;color:#00f;\" id=\"traineeDown0\"></td></tr></table><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Maintaining equality.</p>",
